issue.title: HTTP PreparedRequest for libs
issue.body:
### Abstract

# Problem

If you want to make an API Client library for an HTTP JSON REST API web service,
you are forced to stick with stdlib httpclient, adding JavaScript targets support is complicated,
you have to add `when defined(js):` everywhere, and eventually ends up being a "sea of when".

Sometimes things that work for the Browser may not work for NodeJS, adding even more `when defined(nodejs):`,
and if you want to support other HTTP Clients, like jsfetch, Puppy, Curl wrappers, etc
then code that should be simple becomes really complicated and dense,
so API Clients are forcefuly tied to HTTP Clients, with a lot of complexity added.

I think that adding 1 line to `httpcore` can improve this for the whole Nim ecosystem of libraries,
adding a new public type that can be used for interoperability between API Clients ↔️ HTTP Clients.


### Motivation


# Benefits for Third-party libs


### HTTP Clients

Take as argument the new type `PreparedRequest` by adding a new `func`, that converts a `PreparedRequest`
to a Request "over-the-wire" as fast and optimal as it can. You can even have compile-time `PreparedRequest`.

The HTTP Client benefits that it can be used with all API Clients directly, including JavaScript target ones.


### API Clients

Return using the new type `PreparedRequest` a representation of an specific request to an API endpoint.

API Client benefits that it can be used with all HTTP Clients directly, including JavaScript target ones.


### Benefits for API clients and HTTP Clients

Any HTTP Client can be combined with any API client,
any API client can be combined with any HTTP Client.

All API Clients without JavaScript target support can now run in JavaScript for free.


# Naming

I am using `PreparedRequest` inspired by "PreparedSQL" from Postgres and other contexts,
because it is like a representation of a "pre-made" Request type,
a better naming can be used, if something more descriptive is found.

Feel free to suggest a different name?


# FAQ

- Why just dont do it in a third-party Nimble lib ?

The idea of seamless interoperability of libraries is possible only if a common standard type is in the stdlib.

So any lib can just import it, and use it to return data, and to take as argument too.

- Why stuff like form-data etc is not in the PreparedRequest ?

It is just a formatted `string` in the `body` nothing magical about it.

Your code should format the form-data and put it in the `body` string.

- Why not put it into `httpclient` instead of `httpcore` ?

It is a simple type that can be integrated into `httpcore`, and its just one-liner.

`httpclient` can not be imported on all targets, like JavaScript.

- Why not use `HttpHeaders` instead of `seq[(string, string)]` ?

`HttpHeaders` does not work for all targets, example can not be used for JavaScript targets.

`HttpHeaders` is just a type with 1 `bool` and 1 `Table[(string, string)]` anyways, so is almost the same but simpler.

Can not be used in static contexts, like macros and `const`.

`@{"key": "value", "key": "value"}` for headers works rigth away without too much complications and it is very lightweight.


### Description


# Changes to stdlib

- Add `PreparedRequest` type to `httpcore` as public type.

### PreparedRequest type design

The new type should be something like, this is a one-liner pull request:

```nim
type PreparedRequest* = tuple[httpMethod: HttpMethod, url: Uri, headers: seq[(string, string)], body: string]
```


### Code Examples


### PreparedRequest type design

The new type should be something like, this is a one-liner pull request:

```nim
type PreparedRequest* = tuple[httpMethod: HttpMethod, url: Uri, headers: seq[(string, string)], body: string]
```

Example usage (minimal):

```nim
const example: PreparedRequest = (httpMethod: HttpPost, url: parseUri"http://nim-lang.org", headers: @{"key": "value", "key": "value"}, body: "vodi")
```

Then API Clients (for any arbitrary HTTP API) can add a new func like:

```nim
func someEndpoint*(user: string; age: Positive; someData: SomeType): PreparedRequest =
  # HTTP JSON REST API code here...
```

Then the HTTP Clients (like jsfetch, puppy, curl, etc) can add a new func like:

```nim
func request*(req: PreparedRequest): somelibrary.Response =
  # Request "over-the-wire" code here...
```

Whole example using stdlib (Fake demo):

```nim
import std/[uri, httpcore, httpclient]

# This line goes into httpcore:
type PreparedRequest* = tuple[httpMethod: HttpMethod, url: Uri, headers: seq[(string, string)], body: string]


# This is an API Client (Fake in this example):
func someEndpoint*(user: string; age: Positive; someData: string): PreparedRequest =
  # Some code here for the API endpoint, for this example we just pass thru...
  (httpMethod: HttpPost, url: parseUri"https://httpbin.org/post", headers: @{"k0": user, "k1": $age}, body: someData)


# This is an API Client (httpclient in this example):
proc request*(r: PreparedRequest): Response =
  let
    client = newHttpClient()  # Replace with jsfetch or Puppy or something.
    header = newHttpHeaders(r.headers)
  result = client.request(url = r.url, httpMethod = r.httpMethod, body = r.body, headers = header)
  client.close()

when isMainModule:
  let prepared: PreparedRequest = someEndpoint(user = "pepe", age = 22, someData = "foo")
  echo prepared
  let respon: Response = request(prepared)
  echo respon.body
```


### Backwards Compatibility

No backwards compatibility problems, because it is a new type.

issue.body:
- This modules is for "boilerplate to make unit testing easy" as its documentation says, so I was wondering if we can have a basic string fuzz for unittests.
- Most of the code is actually `runnableExamples`. Works with cpp and js.
- I know llvm libfuzzer but thats huge and complicated and wont run in all targets whatsoever.

comment.body:
So lets imagine someone actually want to use the library linked.

It uses other lib named [`chronicles`](https://github.com/status-im/nim-testutils/blob/6d76fc5e51ce6580289e872558a3b858775e310f/testutils/fuzzing.nim#L1),
`chronicles` depends on [`json_serialization`](https://github.com/status-im/nim-chronicles/blob/master/chronicles.nimble#L12),
`json_serialization` depends on [`serialization`](https://github.com/status-im/nim-json-serialization/blob/master/json_serialization.nimble#L11),
`serialization` depends on [`faststreams`](https://github.com/status-im/nim-serialization/blob/master/serialization.nimble#L11),
`faststreams` depends on [`chronos`](https://github.com/status-im/nim-faststreams/blob/master/faststreams.nimble#L12),
`chronos` depends on [`bearssl`](https://github.com/status-im/nim-chronos/blob/master/chronos.nimble#L12) (C code),
the dependency tree continues, thats just 1 branch of the tree,
why do we end up depending on SSL to do a "Lorem Impsum" string?. 🤷

Bench'in

```nim
import std/[uri, importutils, assertions]
from std/strutils import endsWith  # dollarJuan uses strutils.endsWith
privateAccess Uri.type             # dollarJuan uses Uri.isIpv6
import benchy

func dollarJuan*(u: Uri): string =
  let
    schemeLen:   int = u.scheme.len
    usernameLen: int = u.username.len
    passwordLen: int = u.password.len
    hostnameLen: int = u.hostname.len
    portLen:     int = u.port.len
    pathLen:     int = u.path.len
    queryLen:    int = u.query.len
    anchorLen:   int = u.anchor.len
  var index = 0
  result.setLen(
    schemeLen + usernameLen + passwordLen + hostnameLen + portLen + pathLen + queryLen + anchorLen + 12
  )
  template inserts(item: char or string) =
    when item is string:
      for chara in item:
        result[index] = chara
        inc index
    else:
      result[index] = item
      inc index
  if schemeLen > 0:
    inserts u.scheme
    inserts ':'
    if not u.opaque:
      inserts '/'
      inserts '/'
  if usernameLen > 0:
    inserts u.username
    if passwordLen > 0:
      inserts ':'
      inserts u.password
    inserts '@'
  if u.hostname.endsWith('/'):
    if u.isIpv6:
      inserts '['
      inserts u.hostname[0 .. ^2]
      inserts ']'
    else:
      inserts u.hostname[0 .. ^2]
  else:
    if u.isIpv6:
      inserts '['
      inserts u.hostname
      inserts ']'
    else:
      inserts u.hostname
  if portLen > 0:
    inserts ':'
    inserts u.port
  if pathLen > 0:
    if hostnameLen > 0 and u.path[0] != '/':
      inserts '/'
    inserts u.path
  if queryLen > 0:
    inserts '?'
    inserts u.query
  if anchorLen > 0:
    inserts '#'
    inserts u.anchor
  result.setLen index

proc main() =
  const url: Uri = parseUri"https://nim-lang.org"
  timeIt "dollar\tstd/uri.Uri":
    doAssert $url == "https://nim-lang.org"
  timeIt "dollar\tJuan":
    doAssert dollarJuan(url) == "https://nim-lang.org"

when isMainModule:
  main()
```

pull_request.body:
GCC and Clang have a built-in CLI arguments spell-checker enabled by default,
that runs some Levenshtein-distance suggestions before each compilation,
because it is meant to be run by humans on the CLI typing the arguments.

- Check it yourself runing `clang --help-hidden | grep spell`.
- Continuation of https://github.com/nim-lang/Nim/pull/20503 and https://github.com/nim-lang/Nim/pull/12454

```console
$ gcc -ffast-meth a.c
gcc: error: unrecognized command-line option ‘-ffast-meth’;  did you mean ‘-ffast-math’?
```

issue.title: HTTP PreparedRequest for libs
issue.body:
### Abstract

# Problem

If you want to make an API Client library for an HTTP JSON REST API web service,
you are forced to stick with stdlib httpclient, adding JavaScript targets support is complicated,
you have to add `when defined(js):` everywhere, and eventually ends up being a "sea of when".

Sometimes things that work for the Browser may not work for NodeJS, adding even more `when defined(nodejs):`,
and if you want to support other HTTP Clients, like jsfetch, Puppy, Curl wrappers, etc
then code that should be simple becomes really complicated and dense,
so API Clients are forcefuly tied to HTTP Clients, with a lot of complexity added.

I think that adding 1 line to `httpcore` can improve this for the whole Nim ecosystem of libraries,
adding a new public type that can be used for interoperability between API Clients ↔️ HTTP Clients.


### Motivation


# Benefits for Third-party libs


### HTTP Clients

Take as argument the new type `PreparedRequest` by adding a new `func`, that converts a `PreparedRequest`
to a Request "over-the-wire" as fast and optimal as it can. You can even have compile-time `PreparedRequest`.

The HTTP Client benefits that it can be used with all API Clients directly, including JavaScript target ones.


### API Clients

Return using the new type `PreparedRequest` a representation of an specific request to an API endpoint.

API Client benefits that it can be used with all HTTP Clients directly, including JavaScript target ones.


### Benefits for API clients and HTTP Clients

Any HTTP Client can be combined with any API client,
any API client can be combined with any HTTP Client.

All API Clients without JavaScript target support can now run in JavaScript for free.


# Naming

I am using `PreparedRequest` inspired by "PreparedSQL" from Postgres and other contexts,
because it is like a representation of a "pre-made" Request type,
a better naming can be used, if something more descriptive is found.

Feel free to suggest a different name?


# FAQ

- Why just dont do it in a third-party Nimble lib ?

The idea of seamless interoperability of libraries is possible only if a common standard type is in the stdlib.

So any lib can just import it, and use it to return data, and to take as argument too.

- Why stuff like form-data etc is not in the PreparedRequest ?

It is just a formatted `string` in the `body` nothing magical about it.

Your code should format the form-data and put it in the `body` string.

- Why not put it into `httpclient` instead of `httpcore` ?

It is a simple type that can be integrated into `httpcore`, and its just one-liner.

`httpclient` can not be imported on all targets, like JavaScript.

- Why not use `HttpHeaders` instead of `seq[(string, string)]` ?

`HttpHeaders` does not work for all targets, example can not be used for JavaScript targets.

`HttpHeaders` is just a type with 1 `bool` and 1 `Table[(string, string)]` anyways, so is almost the same but simpler.

Can not be used in static contexts, like macros and `const`.

`@{"key": "value", "key": "value"}` for headers works rigth away without too much complications and it is very lightweight.


### Description


# Changes to stdlib

- Add `PreparedRequest` type to `httpcore` as public type.

### PreparedRequest type design

The new type should be something like, this is a one-liner pull request:

```nim
type PreparedRequest* = tuple[httpMethod: HttpMethod, url: Uri, headers: seq[(string, string)], body: string]
```


### Code Examples


### PreparedRequest type design

The new type should be something like, this is a one-liner pull request:

```nim
type PreparedRequest* = tuple[httpMethod: HttpMethod, url: Uri, headers: seq[(string, string)], body: string]
```

Example usage (minimal):

```nim
const example: PreparedRequest = (httpMethod: HttpPost, url: parseUri"http://nim-lang.org", headers: @{"key": "value", "key": "value"}, body: "vodi")
```

Then API Clients (for any arbitrary HTTP API) can add a new func like:

```nim
func someEndpoint*(user: string; age: Positive; someData: SomeType): PreparedRequest =
  # HTTP JSON REST API code here...
```

Then the HTTP Clients (like jsfetch, puppy, curl, etc) can add a new func like:

```nim
func request*(req: PreparedRequest): somelibrary.Response =
  # Request "over-the-wire" code here...
```

Whole example using stdlib (Fake demo):

```nim
import std/[uri, httpcore, httpclient]

# This line goes into httpcore:
type PreparedRequest* = tuple[httpMethod: HttpMethod, url: Uri, headers: seq[(string, string)], body: string]


# This is an API Client (Fake in this example):
func someEndpoint*(user: string; age: Positive; someData: string): PreparedRequest =
  # Some code here for the API endpoint, for this example we just pass thru...
  (httpMethod: HttpPost, url: parseUri"https://httpbin.org/post", headers: @{"k0": user, "k1": $age}, body: someData)


# This is an API Client (httpclient in this example):
proc request*(r: PreparedRequest): Response =
  let
    client = newHttpClient()  # Replace with jsfetch or Puppy or something.
    header = newHttpHeaders(r.headers)
  result = client.request(url = r.url, httpMethod = r.httpMethod, body = r.body, headers = header)
  client.close()

when isMainModule:
  let prepared: PreparedRequest = someEndpoint(user = "pepe", age = 22, someData = "foo")
  echo prepared
  let respon: Response = request(prepared)
  echo respon.body
```


### Backwards Compatibility

No backwards compatibility problems, because it is a new type.

  if usernameLen > 0:

pull_request.title: Add fno-spell-checking for GCC/Clang
pull_request.body:
GCC and Clang have a built-in CLI arguments spell-checker enabled by default,
that runs some Levenshtein-distance suggestions before each compilation,
because it is meant to be run by humans on the CLI typing the arguments.

- Check it yourself runing `clang --help-hidden | grep spell`.
- Continuation of https://github.com/nim-lang/Nim/pull/20503 and https://github.com/nim-lang/Nim/pull/12454

```console
$ gcc -ffast-meth a.c
gcc: error: unrecognized command-line option ‘-ffast-meth’;  did you mean ‘-ffast-math’?
```

issue.title: HTTP PreparedRequest for libs
issue.body:
### Abstract

# Problem

If you want to make an API Client library for an HTTP JSON REST API web service,
you are forced to stick with stdlib httpclient, adding JavaScript targets support is complicated,
you have to add `when defined(js):` everywhere, and eventually ends up being a "sea of when".

Sometimes things that work for the Browser may not work for NodeJS, adding even more `when defined(nodejs):`,
and if you want to support other HTTP Clients, like jsfetch, Puppy, Curl wrappers, etc
then code that should be simple becomes really complicated and dense,
so API Clients are forcefuly tied to HTTP Clients, with a lot of complexity added.

I think that adding 1 line to `httpcore` can improve this for the whole Nim ecosystem of libraries,
adding a new public type that can be used for interoperability between API Clients ↔️ HTTP Clients.


### Motivation


# Benefits for Third-party libs


### HTTP Clients

Take as argument the new type `PreparedRequest` by adding a new `func`, that converts a `PreparedRequest`
to a Request "over-the-wire" as fast and optimal as it can. You can even have compile-time `PreparedRequest`.

The HTTP Client benefits that it can be used with all API Clients directly, including JavaScript target ones.


### API Clients

Return using the new type `PreparedRequest` a representation of an specific request to an API endpoint.

API Client benefits that it can be used with all HTTP Clients directly, including JavaScript target ones.


### Benefits for API clients and HTTP Clients

Any HTTP Client can be combined with any API client,
any API client can be combined with any HTTP Client.

All API Clients without JavaScript target support can now run in JavaScript for free.


# Naming

I am using `PreparedRequest` inspired by "PreparedSQL" from Postgres and other contexts,
because it is like a representation of a "pre-made" Request type,
a better naming can be used, if something more descriptive is found.

Feel free to suggest a different name?


# FAQ

- Why just dont do it in a third-party Nimble lib ?

The idea of seamless interoperability of libraries is possible only if a common standard type is in the stdlib.

So any lib can just import it, and use it to return data, and to take as argument too.

- Why stuff like form-data etc is not in the PreparedRequest ?

It is just a formatted `string` in the `body` nothing magical about it.

Your code should format the form-data and put it in the `body` string.

- Why not put it into `httpclient` instead of `httpcore` ?

It is a simple type that can be integrated into `httpcore`, and its just one-liner.

`httpclient` can not be imported on all targets, like JavaScript.

- Why not use `HttpHeaders` instead of `seq[(string, string)]` ?

`HttpHeaders` does not work for all targets, example can not be used for JavaScript targets.

`HttpHeaders` is just a type with 1 `bool` and 1 `Table[(string, string)]` anyways, so is almost the same but simpler.

Can not be used in static contexts, like macros and `const`.

`@{"key": "value", "key": "value"}` for headers works rigth away without too much complications and it is very lightweight.


### Description


# Changes to stdlib

- Add `PreparedRequest` type to `httpcore` as public type.

### PreparedRequest type design

The new type should be something like, this is a one-liner pull request:

```nim
type PreparedRequest* = tuple[httpMethod: HttpMethod, url: Uri, headers: seq[(string, string)], body: string]
```


### Code Examples


### PreparedRequest type design

The new type should be something like, this is a one-liner pull request:

```nim
type PreparedRequest* = tuple[httpMethod: HttpMethod, url: Uri, headers: seq[(string, string)], body: string]
```

Example usage (minimal):

```nim
const example: PreparedRequest = (httpMethod: HttpPost, url: parseUri"http://nim-lang.org", headers: @{"key": "value", "key": "value"}, body: "vodi")
```

Then API Clients (for any arbitrary HTTP API) can add a new func like:

```nim
func someEndpoint*(user: string; age: Positive; someData: SomeType): PreparedRequest =
  # HTTP JSON REST API code here...
```

Then the HTTP Clients (like jsfetch, puppy, curl, etc) can add a new func like:

```nim
func request*(req: PreparedRequest): somelibrary.Response =
  # Request "over-the-wire" code here...
```

Whole example using stdlib (Fake demo):

```nim
import std/[uri, httpcore, httpclient]

# This line goes into httpcore:
type PreparedRequest* = tuple[httpMethod: HttpMethod, url: Uri, headers: seq[(string, string)], body: string]


# This is an API Client (Fake in this example):
func someEndpoint*(user: string; age: Positive; someData: string): PreparedRequest =
  # Some code here for the API endpoint, for this example we just pass thru...
  (httpMethod: HttpPost, url: parseUri"https://httpbin.org/post", headers: @{"k0": user, "k1": $age}, body: someData)


# This is an API Client (httpclient in this example):
proc request*(r: PreparedRequest): Response =
  let
    client = newHttpClient()  # Replace with jsfetch or Puppy or something.
    header = newHttpHeaders(r.headers)
  result = client.request(url = r.url, httpMethod = r.httpMethod, body = r.body, headers = header)
  client.close()

when isMainModule:
  let prepared: PreparedRequest = someEndpoint(user = "pepe", age = 22, someData = "foo")
  echo prepared
  let respon: Response = request(prepared)
  echo respon.body
```


### Backwards Compatibility

No backwards compatibility problems, because it is a new type.

pull_request.title: Add fno-spell-checking for GCC/Clang
pull_request.body:
GCC and Clang have a built-in CLI arguments spell-checker enabled by default,
that runs some Levenshtein-distance suggestions before each compilation,
because it is meant to be run by humans on the CLI typing the arguments.

- Check it yourself runing `clang --help-hidden | grep spell`.
- Continuation of https://github.com/nim-lang/Nim/pull/20503 and https://github.com/nim-lang/Nim/pull/12454

```console
$ gcc -ffast-meth a.c
gcc: error: unrecognized command-line option ‘-ffast-meth’;  did you mean ‘-ffast-math’?
```
